Class JsHistory

All Implemented Interfaces:
ObjectLike
public class JsHistory
extends DOM.History.Prototype

An opaque class representing JavaScript client-side objects of the global JsClient.History class.

This class was originally designed to represent the browsing history of a window. For privacy reasons, however, it no longer allows scripted access to the actual URLs that have been visited. The only functionality that remains is in the use of the back(), forward(), and go(Number) methods.

Author:
J.J.Liu (Jianjun Liu) at http://www.jscripter.org
See Also:

Field Detail

length

public static final Value.Number.Member length

An opaque static field defining a member that is named by the field name without a qualifying member and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsHistory object is reference to an integer value specifying the number of URLs in the browser's history list. Since there is no way to determine the index of the currently displayed document within this list, knowing the size of this list is not particularly helpful.

Since:
1.0

back

public final void back()

Goes backward to a previously visited URL.

A call of this method causes the window or frame to which the JsHistory object belongs to revisit the URL (if any) that was visited immediately before the current one. Calling this method has the same effect as clicking on the browser's Back button. It is also equivalent to: 

Js.g().history.go(-1);

Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current object instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

forward

public final void forward()

Goes forward to a previously visited URL.

A call of this method causes the window or frame to which the JsHistory object belongs to revisit the URL (if any) that was visited immediately afters the current one. Calling this method has the same effect as clicking on the browser's Forward button. It is also equivalent to: 

Js.g().history.go(1);

Note that if the browser user has not used the Back button or the Go menu to move backward through the history, and back() and go(Number) methods have not been invoked, invoking this method has no effect because the browser is already at the end of its list of URLs, and there is no URL to go forward to.

Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current object instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

go

public final void go(java.lang.Number relative_position)

Goes to a previously visited URL.

This method takes an integer argument and causes the browser to visit the URL that is the specified number of positions away in the history list maintained by the JsHistory object. Positive arguments move the browser forward through the list, and negative arguments move it backward. Thus, calling Js.g().history.go(-1) is equivalent to calling Js.g().history.back() and produces the same effect as clicking on the Back button. Similarly, Js.g().history.go(3) revisits the same URL that would be visited by calling Js.g().history.forward() three times.

Parameters:
relative_position - The relative position in the history list of the URL to be visited.
Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current object instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

go

public final void go(java.lang.String target_string)

Goes to a previously visited URL.

This method takes a string argument and causes the browser to revisit the first, that is most recently visited, URL that contains the specified string. This form of the method is not well specified and may work differently on different browsers. For example, Microsoft's documentation specifies that the argument must match the URL of a previously specified site exactly, while old Netscape documentation (Netscape created the History object) says that the argument may be a substring of a previously visited URL.

Parameters:
target_string - A URL (or URL fragment) to be visited, if a matching URL exists in the history list.
Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current object instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.
